"Educational Thoughts: How College Exams Can Benefit Both "Academic Elite" and "Underperformers" - Xinhua News."
"Three students from Lanzhou Jiaotong University wrote a letter to the school leaders, expressing their confusion about college exams and proposing an increase in exam difficulty and a change in exam format to truly reflect the students' actual level."
"Indeed, for a long time, college exams have been a "hot topic."
"In the university campus, students come from all over the world, with varying levels of ability, and with varying levels of learning, their learning situations vary greatly."
"For a group with such diverse characteristics, assessment will inevitably result in different experiences."
"Of course, if the exam questions are monotonous, with high repetition and too simple, it will inevitably result in a completely different experience."
"Students who do not study hard may be able to pass the exam by cramming before the exam. If they use other methods, they may achieve twice the result with half the effort."
"As a result, the situation where "underperformers" can pass the exams without putting in much effort, even getting high scores, while "academic elites" who never miss class, have good homework and notes, do not score much higher in exams, becomes a strange reality."
"It seems that the reflection of the problems in college exams by the students of Lanzhou Jiaotong University is not without reason, and it is believed that this situation is not limited to Lanzhou Jiaotong University."
"In this sense, it is worthy of praise for these three students who wrote the letter to express their opinions."
"Actually, those who have been to university are well aware that last-minute studying, seeking various methods to get exam questions from teachers, trying to make sure that the exam covers the materials studied, and even seeking extra help before the exam, as well as cheating during the exam and asking teachers for favors after the exam, are not uncommon."
In my view, as a quality assessment of teaching, the measure of whether a university exam is pass or fail is more about the teacher's comprehensive grasp of teaching and learning, and based on this, scientific proposition.
When entering the undergraduate stage of a university, the major begins to become more specialized, and many major courses mainly focus on basic knowledge.
Undoubtedly, whether one has a comprehensive grasp of the basic knowledge points of a subject is what university exams will test.
Undoubtedly, whether comprehensive mastery of the basic knowledge points of a subject is a content that university exams are to examine. And undergraduate knowledge is basically the basic theories and common sense of the subject. In terms of knowledge points, the space for change is not large and is basically fixed.
As some teachers say, "The basic knowledge of university mathematics learned 20 years ago is still being studied and is still a priority."
But the basic knowledge points remaining the same does not mean the exam questions are single or repeated.
In many universities, exams are generally composed of a question-setting group, and then coordinated by senior subject teachers to form the exam paper. The grading of the exam is also participated by all teachers who are responsible for the subject, which can to some extent overcome the repetition of test questions.
